Project: Wrangle and Analyze Data¶

The objective of this project is to wrangle WeRateDogs (@dog_rates) Twitter data to create an enriched clean dataset that can produce interesting and trustworthy analyses and visualizations.

This notebook contains my code and technical processes. For a summary of the project, approach and outcomes, please see wrangle_report.pdf (technical descriptions) and act_report.pdf (business/public facing summary)

Table of Contents¶

  • Gathering
  • Assessment
  • Cleaning
  • Analysis and Visualizations
  • Conclusions

#Load Twitter API Keys
with open ('twitter_api_credentials','r') as file:
        consumer_key = file.readline()
        consumer_secret = file.readline()
        access_token = file.readline()
        access_secret = file.readline()

auth = tweepy.OAuthHandler(consumer_key,consumer_secret)
auth.set_access_token(access_token,access_secret)

api = tweepy.API(auth, wait_on_rate_limit=True)

tweet_ids = df_archive.tweet_id.values

In [ ]:
#Query the Twitter API for JSON data for each tweet id present in the archives dataframe

count = 0
fails_dict = {}
start = timer()


with open ('tweet_json.txt','w') as file: #the file we want to save the tweet json data to
    for tweet_id in tweet_ids: #loop for each tweet in our .csv file
        count += 1
        print(str(count) + ": " + str(tweet_id))
        try: #try and get the json details for each tweet id in extended mode. If it works, print success. 
            tweet = api.get_status(tweet_id,tweet_mode='extended') #this line is calling the API
            print("Success")
            json.dump(tweet._json, file) #if it works, add the content to the tweet_json.txt file specified as 'file' 
            file.write('\n') #add a new blank line to the file 
        except tweepy.TweepError as e: #if an API error occurs, print Fail and add the tweet id to our fails dictionary
            print("Fail")
            fails_dict[tweet_id] = e
            pass #continue to loop through for the next tweet_id
end = timer()
print(end-start)
print(fails_dict)

Tweet Data has been successfully written to tweet_json.txt. Next step is to extract what we want from that JSON and put it into a Pandas dataframe. The tweets that were deleted will be missing data and can be dropped from the archive dataset later on when we merge tables

In [5]:
#JSON to python dictionary - read the output file previously generated and append the dictionaries to a list called json_data

df_tweet = pd.DataFrame(columns=['tweet_id','retweet_count','favorite_count'])

with open('tweet_json.txt','r') as file:
    for line in file:
        data = json.loads(line) #this line is key for turning json file structure into pandas dictionaries
        tweet_id = data['id']
        retweet_count = data['retweet_count']
        favorite_count = data['favorite_count']
        df_tweet = df_tweet.append(pd.DataFrame([[tweet_id,retweet_count,favorite_count]],columns=['tweet_id','retweet_count','favorite_count']))

Trying to convert a .json file into a pandas dataframe. However, some of the dictionary keys that we want, such as the image URLs, are nested within other dictionaries. Use pd.json_normalize to flatten those dictionaries so that each key can be its own df column. Then we can merge this with the df_tweet containing the top layer keys (i.e. favorite count and retweet count)

Extracting the nested dictionary keys within 'entities'

In [7]:
all_data = []
with open('tweet_json.txt','r') as file:
    for line in file:
        eachDict = json.loads(line)
        #check if entities has a key called media
        if eachDict['entities'].get('media'):
            all_data.append(eachDict)

from pandas.io.json import json_normalize

#['entities','media'] from the 'entities' key, flatten the 'media' dictionary
entities_df = json_normalize(all_data,[['entities','media']], ['id'], record_prefix='entities_')
entities_df['id'] = entities_df['id'].astype('object')

Quality Issues:¶

df_archive:¶

  • Q1) Completeness: 78 entries are replies to other tweets rather than unique entries - these should be removed
  • Q2) Completeness: 181 entries are retweets rather than unique entries - these should be removed
  • Q3) Datatypes: id and all other unique identifiers should be type 'object', timestamp should be type 'datetime'
  • Q4) Validity/Accuracy: In some cases, the ratings are not properly extracted from the tweet text (i.e. tweets with other numbers in the text, tweets with decimal ratings)
  • Q5) Accuracy: there are a few outliers in the rating_numerator, Max = 1776
  • Q6) Validity: there are invalid values in the rating_denominator, leading to unstandardized scores. Max = 170, Min = 0
  • Q7) Accuracy: some dog names are inaccurate, such as 'a', 'the', 'very'...these should all be standardized as 'none'
  • Q8) Consistency: There are different versions of the same dog stages that are not being captured, i.e. "Doggo" or "doggos" in addition to "doggo"

df_predict¶

  • Q9) Datatypes: tweet_id should be type 'object', currently 'int64'. p1, p2, and p3 should be type 'category', currently 'object'

df_api¶

  • Q10) Dataypes: retweet_count and favorite_count should be type 'int64', currently 'object'

Tidiness Issues:¶

  • T1) In archive table, doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo should all be under one categorical column called 'dog_stages'
  • T2) In archive table, the expanded_urls column contains multiple URLs for some tweets
  • T3) Data should be merged into a single dataframe, as all data are focused on the same observational unit (a tweet)

Q5) Accuracy: there are extreme outliers in the rating_numerator, max value is 1776¶

Q6) Validity: there are rating_denominator values > 10 in tweets with more than one dog. These should be normalized.¶

Define

  • Use regex to properly extract ratings from text using str.extract()
  • Split ratings on '/' and update numerator and denominator columns using str.split()
  • Normalize ratings by dividing numerators by denominators
  • Remove outliers by dropping tweets with normalized ratings over a threshold (1.4)

Code:

In [41]:
#use regex to extract more accurate ratings from tweet text and update the rating_numerator and rating_denominator columns
archive_clean['rating'] = archive_clean.text.str.extract('((?:\d+\.)?\d+\/\d{2,})',expand=True)
archive_clean['rating_numerator'],archive_clean['rating_denominator'] = archive_clean['rating'].str.split('/', 1).str

#change datatypes to int to create calculated column
archive_clean['rating_numerator'] = archive_clean['rating_numerator'].astype(float)
archive_clean['rating_denominator'] = archive_clean['rating_denominator'].astype(float)

#create a calculated field with the normalized rating score
archive_clean['rating_score'] = archive_clean['rating_numerator'] / archive_clean['rating_denominator']
archive_clean.sort_values('rating_score',ascending=False)

#drop rating_score outliers that are >1.4 or NaN
archive_clean = archive_clean[(archive_clean.rating_score <= 1.4) & archive_clean.rating_score.notnull()]

#drop the rating_numerator and rating_denominator columns
archive_clean = archive_clean.drop(columns=['rating_numerator','rating_denominator'],axis=1)

A summary of the most common words across the text of all WeRateDogs tweets between November 2015 and August 2017¶

from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)
words = ['https','co','ckin','af']
for word in words:
    stopwords.add(word)
def show_wordcloud(data, title = None):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(
        background_color='black',
        stopwords=stopwords,
        colormap='coolwarm',
        max_words=200,
        max_font_size=60, 
        scale=4,
        random_state=1 # chosen at random by flipping a coin; it was heads
    ).generate(str(data))
    fig = plt.figure(1, figsize=(16, 16))
    plt.axis('off')
    if title: 
        fig.suptitle(title, fontsize=20)
        fig.subplots_adjust(top=2.3)
    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.savefig('wordcloud.jpg')
    plt.show()
# Pass the required data in below function
show_wordcloud(df_clean['text'])

from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS
from PIL import Image
# Concatenate all text from the `text` field
text = df_clean.loc[:, 'text'].str.cat(others=None, sep=' ')
# Read the mask image
# ref: https://openclipart.org/tags/dog%20silhouette
dog_mask = np.array(Image.open('dog_silhouette.jpg'))
# Words to exclude from word cloud
stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)
words = ['https', 'damn','co','ckin','af']
for word in words:
    stopwords.add(word)
# Instantiate word cloud object
wc = WordCloud(background_color='black', max_words=200, mask=dog_mask, colormap='Pastel1',stopwords=stopwords,
              width=1280, height=960)
# Generate word cloud
wc.generate(text)
# Show word cloud
plt.imshow(wc, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.axis('off')

Conclusions¶

In this project, I gathered data on the WeRateDogs Twitter account from three different sources, including a .csv tweet archive file, a .tsv image predictions file hosted on a web server, and a JSON file generated from querying the Twitter API using tweepy. The next step was to assess the data for quality and tidiness, identifying 10 Quality issues and 3 Tidiness issues to be cleaned. I then programmatically cleaned the datasets using python functionalities in the pandas, numpy and regex libraries before merging them into one final clean dataframe. Finally, I used the newly clean data to uncover a handful of insights and visualizations around the WeRateDogs tweet data.

Overall, it was a good learning experience that exposed me to a handful of new capabilities such as gathering data from an API and using regex to extract or manipulate text. It also provided lots of practice with numpy and pandas, which I am becoming increasingly proficient in with each project.
